Date: Mon, 22 Sep 1997 13:07:38 -0400 (EDT)
From: "Dr. Oscar Pedro Larghi" <oplarghi@pinos.com>

The information provided by Henry Tsiang is very important as it is the
service provided worldwide by the Pasteur Institute. However, for the sake
of a fast response, the health authorities of the
neighboring countries should be contacted. El Salvador, Costa Rica,
Guatemala, Honduras, Mexico, Nicaragua and Panama have diagnostic
laboratories, [controlled either [by health or agriculture authorities.
They should be more than willing to help.
Furthermore, Guatemala used to, and probably is now preparing suckling
mouse brain vaccine (SMBV), an excellent product which has helped to
control rabies (canine and bovine) in most Latin American countries.
Argentina is a good example of this. In 1976, the metropolitan area of
Buenos Aires (more than 10 millon inhabitants) had more dog rabies cases
(4700) than any other country in the Americas. With SMBV, the disease was
controled and no rabies cases have been registered since 1984. It was the
first time that rabies was eliminated from a city of that size, in the
history of the disease.
The Pan-American Health Organization should also be contacted for
cooperation in Belize.
